Short answer: Yes — keeping SOPS-encrypted secrets (age recipients) in Git and storing the corresponding private age key on a USB is a viable bootstrap approach for a small self-hosted setup, provided you take a few precautions. It maps well to a GitOps workflow: encrypted secrets live in the repo, and the private key(s) are only provided at build time (from USB or secure runner) so the repo remains safe if leaked.

Below I cover the security tradeoffs, practical bootstrap flows (including first-device steps), recommended hardening and lifecycle practices, and a couple of concrete examples you can apply immediately.

1) Threat model & tradeoffs
- Pros
  - Simple and auditable: secrets are versioned with the repo as encrypted blobs.
  - No central 3rd-party secret store required.
  - Easy to bootstrap a single device offline using a USB.
- Cons / risks
  - USB loss/theft: if the private key on the USB is compromised, any secrets encrypted to that recipient are at risk unless you rotate/revoke the recipient.
  - Single point of recovery: if USB is the only secret copy and it fails, you risk losing the ability to decrypt.
  - Operational friction: distributing keys to multiple maintainers and CI needs extra procedure.

2) Recommended design / best practices
- Always keep public recipients in the repo, never private keys.
- Use age (or sops with age backend) and add multiple recipients:
  - One or more human admins (preferably on hardware tokens) and
  - One CI runner (if CI needs to decrypt for builds).
- Use an encrypted USB (LUKS) to hold private keys, or have the private key on a YubiKey/secure HSM so it never leaves the token.
- Keep backups of private keys in at least two different secure places (e.g., a second encrypted USB in a physical safe and a bank safety deposit), and document recovery procedures.
- Plan for key rotation and revocation: have a process for re-encrypting secrets to new recipients and retiring old recipients.
- Minimal exposure: decrypt only when needed and on trusted builders/operators (your laptop or a protected CI runner). Don't leave unencrypted secret files on disk longer than necessary.
- Audit & CI: validate the repo can be built without secrets (static checks) and only allow secrets-unlocking steps in protected CI runs or manual operator runs.

3) Practical bootstrap flows

A. Quick local-first-device bootstrap (no Terraform required; recommended for initial laptop)
1. Boot the target laptop from a NixOS ISO.
2. Partition/format (you can use `disko` or manual steps).
3. Mount root and install a minimal NixOS with a temporary config or use a live ephemeral system.
4. Clone your repo: git clone <repo>.
5. Unlock & mount your USB that contains the private age key (LUKS recommended), or insert YubiKey.
6. Install sops/age if not already on the live environment.
7. Decrypt secrets locally (or allow sops-nix at build time to read the private key):
